==Copyright status==
[[The Scout Association]] owned the legal [[copyright]] to ''Scouting for Boys'' in the UK, until 31 December 2011, when the copyright expired at the end of the 70th year after the death of its author on 8 January 1941. The book is now in the [[public domain]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Copyright. A guide to reproducing material owned by The Scout Association | publisher = [[The Scout Association]] | url = http://www.ingleboroughscouts.org.uk/factsheets_and_forms/factsheets/Copyright.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate = 2010-02-26 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120303231401/http://www.ingleboroughscouts.org.uk/factsheets_and_forms/factsheets/Copyright.pdf | archivedate = 3 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Until then it could only be reproduced after permission was granted from the Scout Association headquarters, other than for copyright exceptions in specific countries, such as [[fair use]]. The [[Boy Scouts of America]] were granted a special copyright license by Baden-Powell himself for their ''[[Boy Scout Handbook]]'', written during the BSA's formal founding in 1910.<ref name="jeal">{{cite book | first = Tim | last = Jeal | authorlink = Tim Jeal | title = Baden-Powell | publisher = [[Hutchinson (publisher)|Hutchinson]] | location = London| year = 1989 | isbn = 0-09-170670-X }}</ref>

